message.content: Thamnophis sirtalis is a species of nonvenomous colubrid snake commonly known as the common garter snake. It is one of the most widespread and widely recognized snakes in North America. The snake has a long, slender body, with a scale row count of 19. Its color pattern consists of a dark green or black base, with three yellow stripes running down the length of the body. The head is small, with large eyes and a flattened shape. The scales of the snake are smooth and glossy, giving it a sleek appearance. Garter snakes are found in a variety of habitats, including grasslands, forests, and wetlands, and are often seen in suburban and urban areas.
